 unapologetic poaching of \u003cspan\u003e\u003ca data-ga=\"[[\u0026#34;Embedded Url\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;Internal link\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;https://kotaku.com/overwatch-2-skins-characters-reddit-steam-2023-1851119014\u0026#34;,{\u0026#34;metric25\u0026#34;:1}]]\" href=\"https://kotaku.com/overwatch-2-skins-characters-reddit-steam-2023-1851119014\"\u003e\u003cem\u003eOverwatch\u003c/em\u003e’s ideas\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e. From the overall format down to individual hero’s kits, NetEase copiedBlizzard’s homework and didn’t try to change it much. That being said, it’s nice that \u003cem\u003eOverwatch 2\u003c/em\u003e has a direct competitor to put its feet to the fire, and if both of these games must co-exist, they both can learn a lot from each other. Here are six things \u003cem\u003eMarvel Rivals \u003c/em\u003eand \u003cem\u003eOverwatch 2 \u003c/em\u003eshould steal from each other. - Kenneth Shepard \u003cspan\u003e\u003ca data-ga=\"[[\u0026#34;Embedded Url\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;Internal link\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;https://kotaku.com/marvel-rivals-overwatch-2-role-queue-cross-progression-1851749687\u0026#34;,{\u0026#34;metric25\u0026#34;:1}]]\" href=\"https://kotaku.com/marvel-rivals-overwatch-2-role-queue-cross-progression-1851749687\"\u003eRead More\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/div\u003e",
